  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="4" style="c" sid="1CO 4" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="1CO 4:1" />Let a person frame his perception of us this way: that we’re attendants of Christ and stewards of the
        mystery of God. <verse eid="1CO 4:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="1CO 4:2" />In regard to <char style="it">stewardship, </char>it’s a minimum requirement that a person who’s a steward
        be found faithful. <verse eid="1CO 4:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="1CO 4:3" />But it’s not a big deal for me to be examined and then judged by you or by any human tribunal <char style="it">for
        that matter</char>, nor do I judge myself in self-examination. <verse eid="1CO 4:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="1CO 4:4" />In fact, I’m not self-conscious <char style="it">about </char>anything <char style="it">I might’ve done
        wrong</char>, but—no—I haven’t been exonerated of all wrong-doing in this <char style="it">stewardship
        of mine</char>, but the Lord is the one who examines and judges me, <verse eid="1CO 4:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="1CO 4:5" />so that you won’t judge me before the timeframe <char style="it">set aside for judgment</char>, <char
        style="it">that is </char>until the Lord happens to come, who <char style="it">in the course of judging</char>
        will also will illuminate the hidden things of darkness and will put the plans, strategies, intentions,
        and collaborations of the hearts out in the open, and at that time the praise from God to each person
        <char style="it">for what he did right </char>will appear.<verse eid="1CO 4:5" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="1CO 4:6" />But because of you, comrades<char style="sup">[a]</char>, I made the change and applied these things
        to Apollos and me, so that through our<char style="it"> example</char> you would learn the <char style="it">meaning
        of</char> “Don’t be so high-and-mighty that the stuff that’s written <char style="it">in the Bible</char>
        somehow doesn’t apply to you<char style="sup">[b]</char>,” so that your egos don’t become overly-inflated,
        with one person <char style="it">thinking himself to be </char>superior <char style="it">in understanding
        something </char>to the one <char style="it">who explained that something to him in the first place,
        both </char>opposed to someone who has a different <char style="it">opinion</char><char style="sup">[A]</char>.<verse eid="1CO 4:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="1CO 4:7" />Furthermore, who determines what all the different <char style="it">points of view </char>are among you
        and sorts you into categories<char style="it"> based on viewpoint</char>?</para>
    <para style="p" vid="1CO 4:7">What do you have that you didn’t go out and get<char style="sup">[c]</char>? And if you got <char style="it">the
        things you decided to get</char>, why do you carry on<char style="sup">[d]</char> like you never got
        <char style="it">them</char>? <verse eid="1CO 4:7"/>
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="1CO 4:8" />You’ve already gotten plenty enough—<char style="it">you’re</char> already rich—you live like kings<char
        style="sup">[e]</char> <char style="it">when you’re </char>apart from us—it sure would be great if you
        <char style="it">actually </char>became kings, so that we could live like kings together with you. <verse eid="1CO 4:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="1CO 4:9" />You see, I’m thinking that God made an exhibit out of us—the apostles, <char style="it">the</char> lowliest<char
        style="sup">[B]</char><char style="it"> of people</char>—putting us on display, making us appear to everyone
        as though we’re men who’re condemned to death, since we became a spectacle to the world, to angels, and
        to <char style="it">all of </char>mankind. <verse eid="1CO 4:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="1CO 4:10" />We are idiots on account of Christ, but you are logical and sensible in Christ; we are weak, you are
        strong; we are glorious, you are dishonored. <verse eid="1CO 4:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="1CO 4:11" />Up until this very moment in time, we went hungry and thirsty, had no clothes to wear, were beaten, were
        homeless, <verse eid="1CO 4:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="1CO 4:12" />and toiled doing hard manual labor. While being abused, we bless; while being persecuted, we endure;<verse eid="1CO 4:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="1CO 4:13" />while being slandered, we speak softly<char style="sup">[f]</char>. Up until now, we<char style="it">’ve
        been</char> <char style="it">treated </char>like <char style="it">we’re </char>the scum of the world;
        <char style="it">like we’re </char>everyone’s garbage.<verse eid="1CO 4:13" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="1CO 4:14" />I’m not writing these things to shame you or to put you on a guilt trip, rather I’m writing to you as
        though you’re my children, ones who are dear to me, and I’m admonishing, warning, and instructing you
        as such. <verse eid="1CO 4:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="1CO 4:15" />You see, even if you had a million tutors in Christ, you still wouldn’t have<char style="it"> </char>many
        fathers (i.e., those who were instrumental in your conversion) <char style="it">in Christ</char><char
        style="sup">[g]</char>, seeing that I begot you in Christ Jesus through the Gospel. <verse eid="1CO 4:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="1CO 4:16" />So I’m pleading with you: get to where you imitate me<char style="sup">[h]</char>. <verse eid="1CO 4:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="1CO 4:17" />Because of this <char style="it">desire on my part, </char>I sent you Timothy, who is my dear child <char
        style="it">in Christ </char>and who’s faithful in the Lord, who’ll remind you <char style="it">to imitate
        </char>the way I do things in Christ Jesus, just like I teach everyone in churches everywhere.<verse eid="1CO 4:17" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="1CO 4:18" />As I’m not heading in your direction to visit you <char style="it">at the moment</char>, some <char style="it">of
        you</char> have acquired inflated egos. <verse eid="1CO 4:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="1CO 4:19" />But if it was the Lord’s will, I’d leave immediately and travel as quickly as possible to visit you<char
        style="sup">[i]</char>, and I’ll recognize and discern not the message<char style="sup">[j]</char> of
        those who’ve reached the point where their egos are inflated but rather <char style="it">their</char>
        power; <verse eid="1CO 4:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="1CO 4:20" />for the kingdom of God (i.e., God’s interaction with mankind) is not in a message but in power. <verse eid="1CO 4:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="1CO 4:21" />Which would you rather have? That I’d take a staff with me <char style="it">to correct you with </char>when
        I go visit you, or that <char style="it">I’d visit you </char>in<char style="it"> </char>a<char style="it">
        </char>love-spirit and with soft-spoken gentleness?<verse eid="1CO 4:21" />
    </para>
