  <chapter number="8" style="c" sid="1CO 8" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="1CO 8:1" />Now about <char style="it">the issue of eating</char> meat sacrificed to idols, every one of us has <char
        style="it">our own </char>understanding <char style="it">of how this ought to be handled</char>. The
        understanding <char style="it">a person has on a given issue </char>makes him rather full of himself,
        but the love <char style="it">shown in the handling of said issue </char>edifies. <verse eid="1CO 8:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="1CO 8:2" />If any given person thinks he’s reached the point where he’s acquired some <char style="it">level of</char>
        understanding, he has not yet understood <char style="it">the matter </char>as it must be understood.<verse eid="1CO 8:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="1CO 8:3" />If someone loves God, this individual has been known and understood by Him.<verse eid="1CO 8:3" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="1CO 8:4" />So now, about the consumption of food offered to idols: we know for a fact that <char style="it">the
        </char>idols in the world don’t amount to a hill of beans<char style="sup">[a]</char>, and no person
        or thing is God except for One <char style="it">being only</char><char style="sup">[b]</char>. <verse eid="1CO 8:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="1CO 8:5" />Now, granted, there are those who claim there are gods, whether <char style="it">they be </char>in the
        sky, in the atmosphere, among the stars, in a spiritual world beyond that, or on the earth, so that there’re
        many gods and many lords, <verse eid="1CO 8:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="1CO 8:6" />but from our point of view there’s one God the Father, out of Whom <char style="it">are</char> all things,
        and we <char style="it">are returned</char> to Him and to the Lord Jesus Christ, through whom <char style="it">are
        </char>all things, and we <char style="it">are </char>through him.<verse eid="1CO 8:6" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="1CO 8:7" />That aside, we are not <char style="it">on the same level </char>in every <char style="it">aspect of
        </char>understanding. Up until now some people have been in the habit of eating food sacrificed to idols,
        and since their consciences are weak<char style="sup">[A]</char> (i.e., their consciences prod them with
        pangs of guilt over matters they have a deficient understanding of, in this case in regard to food sacrificed
        to idols), they violate<char style="sup">[c]</char> their consciences. <verse eid="1CO 8:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="1CO 8:8" /><char style="it">Eating or not eating this </char>food doesn’t get us anywhere<char style="sup">[d]</char>
        with God: we’re neither worse off if we were to not eat <char style="it">it </char>nor are we better
        off if we were to eat <char style="it">it</char>.<verse eid="1CO 8:8" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="1CO 8:9" />See to it that the right you have <char style="it">to eat such food </char>doesn’t somehow in and of
        itself become a stumbling block<char style="sup">[e]</char> (i.e., an influence for causing sin) for
        those who have a weak<char style="it"> conscience</char>. <verse eid="1CO 8:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="1CO 8:10" />You see, if someone <char style="it">with a weak conscience </char>were to watch you, a person who has
        <char style="it">the</char> <char style="it">correct </char>understanding <char style="it">on this issue,
        </char>sitting at the dinner table<char style="sup">[f]</char> with food sacrificed to idols <char style="it">lying</char>
        <char style="it">on the plate in front of you</char>, wouldn’t his conscience, because it’s in a state
        of weakness, being built up in regard to the eating of foods sacrificed to idols (i.e., because of an
        incorrect understanding in regard to this issue of food sacrificed to idols, his conscience has been
        conditioned to respond with guilt when it ought not)? <verse eid="1CO 8:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="1CO 8:11" />You see, he who’s weak—the comrade<char style="sup">[g]</char> whom Christ died for—is being destroyed
        by your <char style="it">correct </char>understanding. <verse eid="1CO 8:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="1CO 8:12" />In the way that you sin against the comrades and beat on their weak consciences, you sin against Christ.<verse eid="1CO 8:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="1CO 8:13" />That’s why if food causes my comrade to stumble, there’s no way whatsoever that I’ll ever eat sacrificial
        meat again, so that I won’t be a stumbling block to my brother.<verse eid="1CO 8:13" />
    </para>
