  <!--   Chapter  9   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="9" style="c" sid="1CO 9" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="1CO 9:1" />Am I not a freeman? Am I not an apostle (i.e., have I not been sent by God to pioneer the spread of Christianity)?
        Have I not seen our Lord Jesus with my own eyes? Are you not my accomplishment in the Lord? <verse eid="1CO 9:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="1CO 9:2" />If I’m not an apostle <char style="it">sent </char>to <char style="it">root </char>others <char style="it">in
        Christianity</char>, at least I’m <char style="it">an apostle sent </char>to <char style="it">root </char>you;
        in fact, you’re my certificate of authenticity of my having been sent by the Lord. <verse eid="1CO 9:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="1CO 9:3" />My rebuttal to those examining me for the purpose of judging and condemning me is the same.<verse eid="1CO 9:3" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="1CO 9:4" />Do we not have the right to <char style="it">be hosted in such a way that we </char>eat and drink <char
        style="it">for free</char>? <verse eid="1CO 9:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="1CO 9:5" />Do we not have the right to have a fellow-comrade-wife accompany us as she follows our lead<char style="sup">[a]</char>
        <char style="it">on our journeys and have her hosted as well</char>, as all the other apostles of the
        Lord and Peter<char style="sup">[b]</char> <char style="it">do</char>?— <verse eid="1CO 9:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="1CO 9:6" />Or is it just Barnabas and I who don’t have the right to not <char style="it">have to</char> work <char
        style="it">to support ourselves</char>? <verse eid="1CO 9:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="1CO 9:7" />When did any soldier ever serve <char style="it">in the army </char>and<char style="it"> have to</char>
        pay for his own rations? Who plants a vineyard and doesn’t feed off what it produces? Or who cares for
        a ewe and doesn’t feed off the sheep’s milk?<verse eid="1CO 9:7" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="1CO 9:8" />I’m not talking from a human perspective<char style="sup">[c]</char>, or talking <char style="it">about
        concepts </char>that the Law does not also talk about. <verse eid="1CO 9:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="1CO 9:9" />The fact of the matter is, in the Law of Moses it’s written, “Don’t put a muzzle on an oxen while it’s
        threshing <char style="it">wheat</char>.” You don’t think God cares about <char style="it">the</char>
        <char style="it">welfare of </char>the oxen <char style="it">when it’s threshing</char>, do you? <verse eid="1CO 9:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="1CO 9:10" />Or is <char style="it">it that</char> <char style="it">the Law’s </char>addressing <char style="it">this
        topic </char>for our benefit? Furthermore, it’s written <char style="it">in the Law</char> for our benefit
        that the sower ought to sow and the thresher to thresh with the hope of getting a percentage of the harvest.<verse eid="1CO 9:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="1CO 9:11" />If we sowed into you the Holy Spirit-related things<char style="sup">[d]</char> <char style="it">which
        are the backbone of your spiritual lives</char>, is it a big deal if we reap the physical things <char
        style="it">we need to live by </char>from you? <verse eid="1CO 9:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="1CO 9:12" />If others have the right of taking a percentage from you, don’t we all the more so?
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="1CO 9:12">No, we’re not asserting this right; instead we put up with all <char style="it">kinds of </char>things
        so that nothing would hinder the Gospel, the good-news message of Christ. <verse eid="1CO 9:12"/>
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="1CO 9:13" />Don’t you know that they who work the sacred <char style="it">duties in the temple </char>feed on <char
        style="it">the sacrifices offered at</char> the temple; <char style="it">that </char>they who attend
        to the altar divide <char style="it">the spoils </char>of the altar among themselves? <verse eid="1CO 9:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="1CO 9:14" />In the same way the Lord planned for and commanded those who proclaim the Gospel to make their living
        from the Gospel. <verse eid="1CO 9:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="1CO 9:15" />I have not used any of these <char style="it">mandates</char>. I didn’t write about these things to make
        them happen to me; in fact, I’d rather die than have someone invalidate the proud assertions which I
        openly pride myself in. <verse eid="1CO 9:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="1CO 9:16" />Should I proclaim the Gospel, it’s not my place to make proud assertions, you see: by necessity they’re
        imposed on me. I’ll be in deep trouble<char style="sup">[e]</char>, you see, should I not proclaim the
        Gospel. <verse eid="1CO 9:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="1CO 9:17" />If I put this into practice voluntarily, you see, I’ll earn my pay<char style="sup">[f]</char>. If <char
        style="it">I do this</char> voluntarily, I’ve reached the point where I can be entrusted with a managerial
        position. <verse eid="1CO 9:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="1CO 9:18" />So what’s my pay rate? <char style="it">I’m not getting paid a penny s</char>o that I can present the
        Gospel free of charge with a view towards me not exercising my right <char style="it">to receive financial
        support</char> <char style="it">as</char> <char style="it">one who proclaims </char>the Gospel.<verse eid="1CO 9:18" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="1CO 9:19" />Being a freeman, freed from all things, in all things I made myself a slave, so that I’d win over the
        many. <verse eid="1CO 9:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="1CO 9:20" />I became a Jew to the Jews so that I would win over Jews: to those who live under the Law <char style="it">of
        Moses</char>, I <char style="it">let myself be</char> under the Law (<char style="it">though</char> as
        far as my own personal life is concerned, I’m not under the Law), so that I would win over those under
        the Law. <verse eid="1CO 9:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="1CO 9:21" />I became lawless (i.e., not living under the Law of Moses or under any God-based set of rules for that
        matter) to the lawless (<char style="it">though </char>not living lawlessly apart from God, but being
        law-bound as a part of Christ) in order to win over the lawless. <verse eid="1CO 9:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="1CO 9:22" />I became powerless to control my own circumstances<char style="sup">[g]</char> to those who are powerless
        over their circumstances so that I would win over the powerless. I became all things to all people so
        I’d save (i.e., rescue from calamity, spiritual, moral, and otherwise) some. <verse eid="1CO 9:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="1CO 9:23" />But everything<char style="it"> I do, </char>I do for the sake of <char style="it">the</char> <char style="it">proclamation
        of </char>the Gospel so I’d become a workman who specializes in it.<verse eid="1CO 9:23" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="1CO 9:24" />Don’t you know that those who compete in track &amp; field run races but only one of them gets the first-place
        trophy<char style="sup">[A]</char>? Play to win—that’s the way you compete.<char style="sup">[h]</char><verse eid="1CO 9:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="1CO 9:25" />Everyone who competes in athletics trains, and those folks do so in order to get a trophy which can <char
        style="it">and undoubtedly will</char> lose its prestige over time<char style="sup">[i]</char>, but we
        <char style="it">train to win a trophy</char><char style="sup">[j]</char><char style="it"> which </char>will
        always remain prestigious; <verse eid="1CO 9:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="1CO 9:26" />hence, as far as I’m concerned, I don’t <char style="it">train for</char> the race without setting any
        specific personal goals to meet<char style="sup">[k]</char>. I <char style="it">train to </char>box in
        such a way that <char style="it">in the ring </char>I’ll land punches and not wind up with fistfuls of
        air<char style="sup">[l]</char>. <verse eid="1CO 9:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="1CO 9:27" />Uh-uh—I apply strict, punishing disciple to my body (i.e., to my carnal nature in particular), treating
        it roughly and wearing it down; I subdue it and make it my slave, lest I, having proclaimed <char style="it">the
        Gospel to others, </char>should somehow or someway fail to live up to the standard it sets.<verse eid="1CO 9:27" />
    </para>
