  <chapter number="10" style="c" sid="1CO 10" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="1CO 10:1" />I don’t want you to fail to understand this, comrades<char style="sup">[a]</char>, <char style="it">the
        fact </char>that our forefathers—all of them—were <char style="it">always </char>under the cloud <char
        style="it">which they followed after leaving Egypt, </char>and all of them passed through the <char style="it">Red
        </char>Sea, <verse eid="1CO 10:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="1CO 10:2" />and every one of them was initiated into and joined up with Moses in totality<char style="sup">[A]</char>
        by virtue of the cloud and the sea<char style="sup">[b]</char>, <verse eid="1CO 10:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="1CO 10:3" />and every one of them was fed from the same spiritual food, <verse eid="1CO 10:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="1CO 10:4" />and every one of them drank from the same spiritual source: they drank out of the Spiritual Trailing
        Rock (and the rock was Christ).<verse eid="1CO 10:4" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="1CO 10:5" />But God was not pleased with many of them; <char style="it">their dead bodies </char>were strewn about
        the wilderness as we see. <verse eid="1CO 10:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="1CO 10:6" />Now the lives these people led is an example, a pattern, a parallel of our own lives, so that we not
        have strong yearnings bordering on sensual passions for evil, just as some of them had. <verse eid="1CO 10:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="1CO 10:7" />Neither become idolaters, just as some of them did, as it’s written <char style="it">in the Old Testament</char>,
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="1CO 10:7"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="1CO 10:7">The folk-people sat down to eat and drink</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="1CO 10:7">And <char style="it">when they were done </char>got up to play<char style="sup">[B]</char><verse eid="1CO 10:7"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="1CO 10:8" />Nor commit fornication (i.e., behave in a sexually immoral way), just as some of them committed fornication,
        and <char style="it">as a result </char>twenty-three thousand dropped dead in one day. <verse eid="1CO 10:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="1CO 10:9" />Nor test Christ (i.e., use a circumstance as a test to see if Christ will pass from your point of view),
        just as some of them tested him and <char style="it">as a result </char>were destroyed by serpents. <verse eid="1CO 10:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="1CO 10:10" />Nor grumble, murmur, or complain just as some of them grumbled and <char style="it">as a result </char>were
        destroyed by the Destroyer.<verse eid="1CO 10:10" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="1CO 10:11" />Now those things <char style="it">that happened to them </char>turned out to be an example, a pattern,
        a parallel of our own lives, and it was recorded <char style="it">in the Bible</char> to make us aware
        <char style="it">that this applies to us</char>, whom the ends of the ages<char style="sup">[C]</char>
        have arrived at and are staring us in the face, <verse eid="1CO 10:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="1CO 10:12" />so that the one who thinks he stands (i.e., the one who thinks he’s immune to sin) should see to it that
        he doesn’t fall (i.e., fall to sin). <verse eid="1CO 10:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="1CO 10:13" />No temptation has been taken hold of <char style="it">by the person being tempted </char>if it were not
        for the fact that humans are susceptible to it. But God is faithful, Who won’t permit us to be tempted
        beyond what we’re capable of. No, He’ll make an exit <char style="it">strategy </char>consisting of the
        ability to bear <char style="it">the temptation</char> while under the weight of it.<verse eid="1CO 10:13" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="1CO 10:14" />Therefore, my dear <char style="it">comrades</char>, get as far away from the idolatry <char style="it">you’re
        surrounded with </char>as fast as you can<char style="it">.</char> <verse eid="1CO 10:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="1CO 10:15" />I’m talking <char style="it">to you </char>as <char style="it">though I’m speaking</char> to sensible
        people. You decide <char style="it">the sensibility of </char>what I’m saying. <verse eid="1CO 10:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="1CO 10:16" />The cup of blessing (i.e., the cup of communion wine) which we pronounce a blessing <char style="it">with</char>,
        is it not an intimate association with the blood of Christ? The loaf of bread which we break <char style="it">during
        communion</char>, is it not an intimate association with the body of Christ<char style="sup">[D]</char>?<verse eid="1CO 10:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="1CO 10:17" />Because <char style="it">the </char>loaf is a single entity, <char style="it">we </char>the many are
        one body; we all partake <char style="it">of pieces which come </char>out of the one <char style="it">loaf</char>,<char
        style="it"> </char>you see. <verse eid="1CO 10:17" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="1CO 10:18" />Take a look at Israel, physically speaking: don’t they who feed themselves with the meat of the sacrificial
        animals have an intimate association with the altar and share in the work which goes on there? <verse eid="1CO 10:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="1CO 10:19" />So what exactly am I trying to tell you<char style="sup">[c]</char>? That idolatry is something <char
        style="it">which needs to be taken seriously</char><char style="sup">[d]</char>? Or that food sacrificed
        to an idol is something <char style="it">which needs to be taken seriously</char>? <verse eid="1CO 10:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="1CO 10:20" />Uh-uh—What they sacrifice they sacrifice to demons and not to God; I don’t want an intimate association
        between you and demons to form. <verse eid="1CO 10:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="1CO 10:21" />You can’t be drinking from the Lord’s cup (i.e., following the Lord’s plan for your lives<char style="sup">[e]</char>)
        and from demons’ cup; you can’t be partaking of the Lord’s table (i.e., receiving the Lord’s provision
        for your nourishment<char style="sup">[f]</char>, and for all of your needs for that matter) and of the
        demons’ table. <verse eid="1CO 10:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="1CO 10:22" />Or do you <char style="it">intend to</char> provoke the Lord to wrath<char style="sup">[g]</char>? We
        aren’t more powerful than he, are we?<verse eid="1CO 10:22" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="1CO 10:23" />Everything is permissible, but not everything is beneficial.<char style="sup">[h]</char> Everything is
        permissible, but not everything edifies. <verse eid="1CO 10:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="1CO 10:24" />Let no one pursue his own interests <char style="it">exclusively</char><char style="sup">[i]</char> but
        the next person’s <char style="it">as well</char>. <verse eid="1CO 10:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="1CO 10:25" />Eat any sort of meat which is sold at the marketplace without any qualms<char style="sup">[j]</char>;
        <char style="it">the Bible says,</char> <verse eid="1CO 10:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="1CO 10:26" />“The abundant, splendid variety of things that the earth contains was put there by the Lord’s doing<char
        style="sup">[k]</char>,” you see. <verse eid="1CO 10:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="1CO 10:27" />If someone who’s an unbeliever invites you over <char style="it">to his house </char>and you want to
        go, eat everything that’s laid out on the table or put on your plate without having any qualms about
        eating any of it. <verse eid="1CO 10:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="1CO 10:28" />If someone were to tell you, “This is meat which was sacrificed <char style="it">in a pagan ritual</char>,”
        don’t eat it on account of that person who pointed it out and because of <char style="it">the </char>misgivings
        <char style="it">surrounding it</char>—<verse eid="1CO 10:28" />
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="1CO 10:29" />I don’t mean because of your own misgivings but because of the other person’s. Now just why is what I’m
        free to do or not do decided by another person’s misgivings? <verse eid="1CO 10:29" />
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="1CO 10:30" />If I partake <char style="it">in the eating of certain foods </char>by means of grace (i.e., using the
        license I’ve been given), why are terrible things said about me in connection with He Whom I offer up
        thanksgiving to? <verse eid="1CO 10:30" />
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="1CO 10:31" />So whether you eat <char style="it">or don’t eat something </char>or whether you drink <char style="it">or
        don’t drink something </char>or whether you do <char style="it">or don’t do anything else</char>, everything
        <char style="it">you end up doing</char>, do to God’s glory. <verse eid="1CO 10:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="1CO 10:32" />Get to where you’re not inadvertently causing a Jew or Westerner<char style="sup">[l]</char> or <char
        style="it">anyone in </char>God’s church to get offended or to fall to temptation, <verse eid="1CO 10:32" />
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="1CO 10:33" />just as I too try to fit in with everyone <char style="it">by not offending them or causing alarm among
        them</char>, not pursuing my own interests but rather <char style="it">the interests </char>of the<char
        style="it"> </char>majority, so that they might be saved.<verse eid="1CO 10:33" />
    </para>
